'''Trev''' is slang in [[New Zealand]] for a farm assistant or other rural worker - the ordinary country bloke. This term, though no longer as popular as it was during the [[1970s]] and [[1980s]], originated with the comedy character of [[Fred Dagg]], created by [[John Morrison Clarke|John Clarke]]. Fred Dagg was the archetypical New Zealand farmer, and - much like [[Monty Python]]'s famous sketch involving an Australian university over-run with lecturers called Bruce - was constantly surrounded by people called Trev. Such was the popularity of the Fred Dagg character (raised to [[folk hero]] status in New Zealand in the 1970s) that several words and phrases associated with him entered the language.

In the [[United Kingdom]], it is often seen as a [[synonym]] of [[Chav]].

